⚡ Why Lambda is Required?

Amazon Bedrock Agent:

✅ Understands natural language

✅ Makes intelligent decisions

❌ However, it cannot directly access AWS resources like EC2, EBS, or Elastic IP.

👉 Therefore, we use AWS Lambda:

🧠 + 🖐️ AI + Lambda Model

Bedrock Agent = Brain (understands & decides)

Lambda = Hands (executes AWS actions)



🔧 Lambda Functions Used
1️⃣ discover_cost_resources

Scans the AWS account

Identifies unused or chargeable resources

Examples:

Unattached EBS volumes

Unused Elastic IPs



2️⃣ delete_cost_resource

Deletes only user-approved resources

Executes only after user types: CONFIRM

Ensures safe and controlled operations




🔐 IAM Role for Lambda (Critical Step)

To allow Lambda to interact with AWS services, we create an execution role.



🎯 Purpose of this Role

Enables Lambda to:

Read AWS resources (Describe APIs)

Delete only specific resources (EIP, EBS, Snapshots)

Follows the Principle of Least Privilege 🔒



🪜 Step-by-Step: Create IAM Role

🪜 Step 1: Open IAM

Navigate to: IAM → Roles

Click Create role



🪜 Step 2: Select Trusted Entity

Select: AWS Service

Under use case:

Choose Lambda

Click Next



🪜 Step 3: Attach Basic Policy

Search and select:

✅ AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole

👉 This provides:

CloudWatch logging

Basic execution permissions




🪜 Step 4: Name the Role

Role Name:
BedrockCostAgentLambdaRole

Description:
Allows Lambda functions to call AWS services for cost optimization tasks

Click Create role

➕ Step 5: Attach Custom Inline Policy

Now we assign permissions for AWS resource access.



🪜 Step 5.1: Open the Role

Search for: BedrockCostAgentLambdaRole

Open it

Click Add permissions → Create inline policy



🪜 Step 5.2: Add Policy (JSON)

Switch to JSON editor

Paste the policy from iam role and policy json code


🪜 Step 5.3: Policy Capabilities
🔍 Read Permissions

ec2:DescribeInstances

ec2:DescribeVolumes

ec2:DescribeSnapshots

ec2:DescribeAddresses

ec2:DescribeNatGateways

❌ Safe Delete Permissions

ec2:ReleaseAddress (Elastic IP)

ec2:DeleteVolume

ec2:DeleteSnapshot

👉 Only specific and controlled actions are allowed



🪜 Step 5.4: Name Policy

Policy Name:
BedrockCostAgent-DiscoveryPolicy

Click Create policy

✅ Final Result

Your IAM Role will include:

✅ AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole

✅ BedrockCostAgent-DiscoveryPolicy



🧠 Architecture Summary
User → Bedrock Agent → Lambda → AWS Services

Agent decides what to do

Lambda executes the action

IAM Role controls what is allowed



🔥 Key Takeaway

Without Lambda and IAM Role, the AI agent can only think.

With Lambda, it can act safely and intelligently 🚀
